---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Editorial Team | classactionsettlementcalc.com';
const description = 'Meet the editorial team behind classactionsettlementcalc.com — class action and complex litigation specialists who review every page for accuracy.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>Every page on classactionsettlementcalc.com is written and reviewed by editors with direct experience in class action litigation, settlement administration, and complex civil procedure. No page is published without editorial review, and no sponsored or paid content appears on this site.</p>

  <h2>Class Action &amp; Complex Litigation Practice</h2>
  <p>Our editorial team leads the editorial team and is responsible for the calculator methodology, allocation analysis, and all primary content on this site. This side of the team&rsquo;s background is in class action litigation support, with specific experience in Rule 23 certification standards, settlement approval proceedings under Fed. R. Civ. P. 23(e), allocation plan design across consumer fraud and securities fraud case types, attorney fee analysis under the common fund doctrine, and claims administration for large consumer and securities settlements. This side of the team reviews all methodology content and is the final editorial authority on the accuracy of the calculator&rsquo;s distribution estimates.</p>
  <p>The claims rate baselines, allocation multipliers, and incentive award estimates documented on the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a> reflect this team&rsquo;s analysis of published class action settlement administrations across consumer, securities, employment, and data breach case types.</p>

  <h2>Settlement Procedure &amp; Claims Reference</h2>
  <p>Our team also contributes to guide and FAQ content, specializing in the claims filing process, opt-out rights and procedures, cy pres distributions, CAFA coupon settlement standards, and the practical mechanics of class action distribution for ordinary class members. This side of the team&rsquo;s background includes civil litigation research and class action settlement monitoring, providing the procedural and claims-process perspective that is most relevant to class members trying to understand and maximize their individual recovery.</p>

  <h2>Editorial Standards</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Primary source grounding:</strong> Factual claims about class action procedure are sourced to the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, leading circuit court decisions on certification and settlement approval, and published settlement administration data — not to secondary summaries.</li>
    <li><strong>Documented methodology:</strong> Calculator allocation multipliers, claims rate baselines, and fee assumptions are documented in full on the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>No sponsored content:</strong> Monetized through Google AdSense display advertising only. No sponsored articles, paid placements, or attorney referral arrangements.</li>
    <li><strong>Currency:</strong> Pages are reviewed and updated when significant class action doctrine changes — new circuit decisions on cy pres, CAFA coupon settlement standards, or Rule 23 amendment guidance.</li>
    <li><strong>Scope clarity:</strong> This site provides informational content only — not legal advice or case-specific predictions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Corrections Policy</h2>
  <p>If you identify a factual error — an incorrect procedural rule citation, a claims rate that is inconsistent with published administration data, or a settlement calculation that does not follow the documented methodology — email <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. Include the specific claim and your source. Corrections are reviewed within five business days.</p>

  <p>Return to the <a href="/">calculator</a> or see the <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
